00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:19.160
So what is React log?

00:02:19.160 --> 00:02:27.199
React log is a snapshot or log of all the reactive interactions within a Shiny application.

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:32.240
So just so that we're all on the same page, let's review this for just a quick second.

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:36.960
So reactive programming, it's a paradigm concerned with propagation of change.

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:39.639
You need to remember a lot of things.

00:02:39.639 --> 00:02:42.080
There's three types that we always talk about.

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:49.119
We have our sources, such as input key A. We have conductors, such as a reactive.

00:02:49.119 --> 00:02:55.919
Where I create a new value, given that input key A. And then I have some end points.

00:02:55.919 --> 00:02:59.520
Such as output key B, which is one of my many render functions.

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:02.080
In this case, render print.

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:07.360
Or we could have an observe, where the propagation ends there at the observe statement.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:12.160
If we were to kind of look at a dependency tree of this, it would look similar to this.

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:18.000
Where we have an input, such as key A, going into value, which was then used in output

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.039
key B, or even the observe statement.

00:03:21.039 --> 00:03:27.960
And we'll get into a more in depth look at that later.

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:28.960
So React log.

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:34.399
We're gonna set up this dependency tree, and then we're gonna traverse backwards and forwards

00:03:34.399 --> 00:03:37.199
through this reactivity history.

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:40.720
We're also going to be able to search for reactive elements.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:46.759
Because even though we all love our hello world applications, we're building some complex

00:03:46.759 --> 00:03:47.759
applications.

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:51.119
So we need to search for that.

00:03:51.119 --> 00:03:53.839
Once we've searched for them, we want to filter.

00:03:53.839 --> 00:04:02.199
So we can filter down and make our large complex app a very small, interactive, tiny dependency

00:04:02.199 --> 00:04:03.199
tree.

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:09.619
And then that way we can explore efficiently as to where our errors are coming from.

00:04:09.619 --> 00:04:14.399
And then before I show the demo on this, it's built on Cytoscape JS, which is a really nice

00:04:14.399 --> 00:04:19.839
JavaScript graph library, because that's what we're doing here.

