00:14:04.679 --> 00:14:08.840
So some things to remember for the reactive coding.

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:12.460
Any outputs that are not visible are not calculated.

00:14:12.460 --> 00:14:13.520
This is on purpose.

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:19.200
This is a direct design decision by Shiny, so you may see some output elements that just

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:21.820
hang out invalidated forever.

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:23.239
They're not on display.

00:14:23.239 --> 00:14:29.780
So you may need to open that second tab or do something else with that.

00:14:29.780 --> 00:14:35.880
If new reactive elements are created for every user interaction, such as a click or an input

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:41.960
value change, you've probably coded what's referred to as an anti-solution.

00:14:41.960 --> 00:14:46.880
Joe talks about this in his Shiny DevCon presentation.

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:51.280
And what it will do with React Log is it will cause the React Log to explode.

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:56.340
It'll get very big because more reactives will be done for every user interaction.

00:14:56.340 --> 00:14:58.520
So if this happens, it's okay.

00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:01.719
Your Shiny app isn't exploding on memory, I promise.

00:15:01.719 --> 00:15:07.520
There's garbage collection going on, but the graph will be quite big right now.

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:10.479
And then React Log is not a performance debugger.

00:15:10.479 --> 00:15:12.039
It's a reactivity debugger.

00:15:12.039 --> 00:15:16.679
If you want performance debugging or inspection, please use Profiz.

00:15:16.679 --> 00:15:25.679
It's very good at that and it will tell you very quickly where to change your code.

00:15:25.679 --> 00:15:27.479
And then last word of caution.

00:15:27.479 --> 00:15:33.940
Do not keep React Log enabled when deploying to production.

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:39.599
Your memory will be very mad at you when we're all done.

00:15:39.599 --> 00:15:40.960
So future ideas.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:44.520
I want to visually differentiate user sessions.

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:46.479
Right now everything is all displayed as one graph.

00:15:46.479 --> 00:15:50.840
You may have independent graphs show up, which is just fine, but it's nice to maybe silo

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:58.640
off a user so that it's very visual as to what's happening at one time.

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:04.119
We also want to display the values of the outputs and reactive values.

00:16:04.119 --> 00:16:08.859
Currently we only have it for the input values, but that's how a standard React Log is working.

00:16:08.859 --> 00:16:14.359
So that will come up in the next version of React Log.

00:16:14.359 --> 00:16:17.239
We also want to do expandable and collapsible groups.

00:16:17.239 --> 00:16:21.200
This is one of my favorite ideas about this project.

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:24.280
Things such as render plot.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:29.840
Render plot actually inserts like four or five different reactive values for every render

00:16:29.840 --> 00:16:31.479
plot function.

